    rationale: "This presentation is classic for benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV). Otoconia (calcium carbonate crystals) dislodge from the utricle and migrate into a semicircular canal (most commonly the posterior canal). Head movement causes these particles to shift, generating abnormal endolymph currents that stimulate hair cells inappropriately, producing brief (< 60 seconds) positional vertigo without hearing loss or tinnitus. Orthostatic hypotension (A) causes presyncope \u2014 a feeling of faintness \u2014 not true spinning vertigo. Endolymphatic hydrops (C) is the mechanism of M\u00e9ni\u00e8re's disease, which presents with the triad of vertigo + hearing loss + tinnitus. Demyelination (D) would cause persistent, not positional, vestibular symptoms.",
