    rationale: "In thyroid eye disease (Graves' ophthalmopathy), glycosaminoglycan deposition and inflammatory infiltration expand the orbital contents, pushing the globe forward (proptosis) and causing lid retraction. The combination of proptosis and lid retraction mechanically prevents the eyelids from fully apposing, resulting in lagophthalmos. This is distinct from Bell's palsy, where CN VII weakness reduces orbicularis oculi contractile force. Levator hyperactivity contributes to lid retraction but is not the primary cause of lagophthalmos. Tarsal scarring is not the mechanism in thyroid eye disease.",
    metadata: { topic: "lagophthalmos", priority: "high" },
