    rationale: "Loss of the left visual field in both eyes (left homonymous hemianopsia) indicates a lesion in the right visual pathway posterior to the optic chiasm \u2014 specifically the right optic tract, right lateral geniculate nucleus, right optic radiation, or right occipital cortex. This is because fibers from the nasal retina of each eye cross at the chiasm, so the right hemisphere processes the left visual field from both eyes. A left optic nerve lesion would cause monocular vision loss in the left eye only. A chiasmal lesion typically causes bitemporal hemianopsia. A left optic tract lesion would cause right homonymous hemianopsia.",
