    rationale: "The finding described is ectropion (outward turning of the lower lid). When the lower lid everts, the inferior punctum is displaced away from the medial tear lake, preventing normal capillary drainage of tears into the canaliculus. This impaired drainage mechanism causes epiphora despite normal or even reduced lacrimal secretion. Nasolacrimal duct obstruction would also cause epiphora but would be confirmed by the regurgitation test, not by lid position. Reflex tearing from trigeminal stimulation would require a corneal or conjunctival irritant.",
