    rationale: "Thyroid eye disease (Graves' ophthalmopathy) is driven by TSH receptor antibodies (TRAb) that cross-react with TSH receptors on orbital fibroblasts. This stimulates fibroblasts to produce glycosaminoglycans (particularly hyaluronic acid), which are highly hydrophilic and cause expansion of orbital fat and extraocular muscles. The resulting increase in orbital volume pushes the globe forward (proptosis) and causes lid retraction and restricted motility. Elevated T4 does not directly cause orbital fat hypertrophy. Autoimmune destruction causes inflammation and enlargement, not primary fibrosis. Sympathetic overstimulation contributes to lid retraction but does not cause true proptosis.",
